Tree Form. You can use an action to plant one end of the staff in fertile earth and expend 1 charge to transform the staff into a healthy tree. The tree is 60 feet tall and has a 5-foot-diameter trunk, and its branches at the top spread out in a 20-foot radius. The tree appears ordinary but radiates a faint aura of transmutation magic if targeted by detect magic. While touching the tree and using another action to speak its command word, you return the staff to its normal form. Any creature in the tree falls when it reverts to a staff.


Spells - The Magic of Deepwater
Scholar’s Touch
Source: Races of Destiny (3.5)
1st-level divination (ritual)

Casting Time: 1 action
Range: Touch
Components: V, S
Duration: Concentration, up to 1 minute

You can touch any book or scroll and absorb the knowledge contained within as if you had just read it. This is equivalent to a solid reading but not deep study. The character does not gain perfect recall of the information, just whatever he would have gotten from reading it completely once. If you can't read the language of the source, the spell has no effect. This spell cannot be used to prepare spells or to cast magical scrolls, nor does it have any effect when reading a magical book (such as a tome of understanding).

Wood Shape
Source: Player’s Handbook (3.5)
2nd-level transmutation

Casting Time: 1 action
Range: Touch
Components: V, S
Duration: Instantaneous

You touch a piece of wood, which may be a Large or smaller tree or wooden object or a section of wood that fits entirely within a 10-foot cube, and cause it to twist into any shape you desire. The extent of these changes can't cause the wood to extend beyond 10 feet in any dimension. While it is possible to make crude coffers, doors, and so forth, fine detail isn't possible. You can also create simple melee weapons, such as a club, greatclub, or quarterstaff, using this spell, but shields, armor, and martial or ranged weapons are too complex to create.

Explore Deepwater
The adventure begins in the wizardly study of Carlatwin Verbos. If you are using this as the starting point of the adventure, the party can just begin there, otherwise, have the party find a flyer asking for an adventurers party to complete a quest, with a 5000 gp payment upfront, and a doubling upon completion.
The physical location of Carlatwin’s study does not matter. If you are inserting this into a pre-existing campaign, you can place it anywhere, as long as it's near the sea. If you don’t have a pre-established location, use the town of Newlisthyme. Begin with this narration:
Newlisthyme is a small port town nestled in green rolling hills, the ocean stretching out endlessly along the horizon. The town itself is rather unnoteworthy, merely being a small collection of residences and markets that sell to the local fishermen. Upon the westward hill, rising high in the sky, lies the tower of the reclusive Carlatwin Verbos, where you find yourself speaking to the great wizard Verbos, answering his call for a party willing to complete a simple quest.
Carlatwin is a shifty goblin, who’s rather infamous for his abilities as a pickpocket. He will take any and all opportunities to steal from the party, not being dissuaded until openly threatened, and even then still taking opportunities when they arise. He is a cowardly wizard who will typically avoid combat at all costs, but is more than capable of taking on the level 5 party by himself.
He is asking the party to complete a quest for him, deliver a medallion with a blue stone to an island called Deepwater, off the coast of Newlisthyme. He’ll provide the travel in the form of a fishing captain who owes him a favor, and is offering the party 5000 gp each now, to accept the quest, and an additional 5000 gp upon completion of the quest. Upon accepting, Carlatwin produces the artifact for delivery:
Carlatwin reaches into the pocket of his oversized jacket and removes a medallion: a beautifully ornate golden frame, set with the most beautiful blue/purple gemstone that you have ever seen. Fractals of color move across the stone as it turns in the light, casting a shimmering ambience around the room. Any mage can immediately detect an immense amount of magic emanating from the stone.
Carlatwin will inform the party that all they must do is transport this amulet to Deepwater island, and their payouts will be doubled upon their return. It is very obvious to the players that the goblin is hiding something, but what he’s hiding is impossible to discern. Ultimately, the 10,000gp each reward for completing the quest should be enough to convince the party.
Upon agreeing, Carlatwin teleports himself and the entire party down to a boat on the dock known as the Mother Keel. A small shipping vessel captained by the dwarf Theorock the Bald. Theorock and Carlatwin have a strange relationship where they are more or less forced to work together due to the lack of anybody else useful in the town of Newlisthyme. Carlatwin is the only mage able to offer magic services to Theorock, and Theorock is the only captain willing to smuggle black market goods in and out of the port.
When Carlatwin teleports the party aboard the Mother Keel, it's apparent that Theorock was expecting them, but is still not happy about having to see Carlatwin. The two don’t speak to one another, and instead Carlatwin informs the party that they must travel 14 nautical miles directly offshore where they will find the island they are looking for. Importantly, Theorock does not hear these instructions. Afterwards, Carlatwin teleports away, informing the party that their payment is on the boat (there is 5000gp for each member of the party).
When the party enters the boat, Theorock begins departing, if the characters say they want to do something first, Theorock will tell them that Carlatwin’s orders were to get this done as soon as possible, and he isn’t going to wait. This is primarily to prevent the players from spending any of the money until they reach Deepwater. There’s nothing wrong with the money, but 5000 gp is a lot for level 5 characters and is better spent in Deepwater than in standard shops and towns.
The boat ride goes smoothly, and Theorock doesn’t speak unless the party forces him into conversation, and even then is short with his answers. It’s apparent that he isn’t doing this out of kindness or friendship, and is likely receiving a payment the same way the party is. As the boat approaches the 14 NM mark, Theorock will ask for clarification of where to go next. When the party tells him the island is 14 nautical miles straight out, he’ll insist that there’s nothing there and that he sails these waters daily. If the party is not able to offer a sufficient explanation, he will begin becoming angry and belligerent:
Theorock turns from the helm and spits angrily, a vein pulses on his forehead and he clenches his fists. Right as it seems like he might be about to lose control, a cloud of fog swallows the ship, manifesting seemingly out of nowhere. The moment the fog touches each member of the party, they can hear a faint singing. Theorock immediately stops being angry, goes slackjawed, and stands still as if in a trance.
The singing grows louder as the fog becomes so thick you can’t see outside the edge of the boat. Then as quickly as it appeared, the fog vanishes and as it does, the singing reaches a crescendo. 
The whole party must make a DC10 wisdom saving throw. Any players who succeed can subsequently make a DC15 perception check. On a success, they immediately recognize the effects of the fabled sirens, and know to plug their ears and the ears of anyone who failed the initial WIS saving throw. 
Anyone who fails is entranced and can no longer do anything but look around. They can still see, hear, and make checks to understand what is happening around them, but they are unable to move, speak, or act in any way. This effect lasts until their ears are somehow plugged, or until they enter the borders of Deepwater. Regardless of what happens with the party, Theorock will turn the boat towards Deepwater island, activate a magical rune that detaches the steering wheel from the helm, and then walk off the edge of the boat and fall into the water. If the players try to prevent this, Theorock will move faster than what seems possible for a dwarf, and they will be unable to stop him. The only way to prevent this is by incapacitating Theorock before entering the fog, tying him up, and then entering the fog by themselves. Theorock isn’t designed to survive past this point, so If they do this, you can do whatever you want with his aspect of the story. 
If all members of the party fail the initial WIS saving throw, Theorock jumps into the water, and the boat slams into the “shore” of Deepwater, amongst hundreds of other boats. The charm ends the moment the boat crashes:
As the boat’s speed reaches a peak, a mountainous graveyard of ships, masts, and hulls eclipses the sky in front of you. Hundreds of ships; some full sized pirate frigates with huge masts adorned with the skull and crossbones of old crews, others small fishing trawlers, and sail boats. Theorock’s small boat slams into the hull of a large frigate, breaching through the rotting hull, and knocking everyone prone. 
The sirens can be glimpsed by the party, watching them from cracks and from the water, but they don’t seem hostile now that the ship has crashed. If the party tries to free the boat or examine the damage, it seems as if Theorock’s boat has somehow melded into the hull of the rotting frigate, as if the wood from the two ships had been welded together. The party is unable to remove the boat from the wreckage. As the party finds their way out of the hull of this rotting boat, they climb to the top of the graveyard of ships, revealing the island of Deepwater about 200 feet away:
As you climb up onto the hull of another boat, its mast cracked and fallen over across the ship’s helm, you finally get a good look at your destination. The most notable thing is the sky, above you is a beautiful smattering of stars and auroras, backed by a soft purple glow in the night sky. Despite this, you find yourselves able to see through the apparent darkness easily. 
Regardless of what time it was when you entered, it is always “night” time in Deepwater. Any creatures or races with sunlight vulnerabilities like Drow and Vampires do not suffer from those effects here. When outdoors, creatures without darkvision can see the normal distance they would be able to during the day. This doesn’t apply to places like inside the cave.
In front of you lies Deepwater island, about 5 miles across, and surrounded on all sides by this graveyard of boats. At the center of the island sits an enormous mesa of inky black stone. From where you stand you can faintly see what appears to be the entrance to a cave on the side of the mountain. Surrounding the mountain is a forest of tall trees, all of which are of various black and purple hues. You can still hear the sirens’ song, but it seems to no longer have any effect on you.
All of the boats have already been picked clean, and most of them are rotting and falling apart. If the players search, it immediately becomes apparent that there is nothing to find out here. As the party moves inland, if they examine the black and purple trees, they will find they are exactly identical to the plants they are familiar with, the colors are just strange. 

As the party enters the cave, read:
The air cools as you move down the thin ledge leading into the cavern. A faint music can be heard over the soft lapping of the waves against the rocks. Carried along by a breeze that smells of salt and sea water.
As you move down the path, the thin ledge opens up into a wooden pathway that sort of resembles a dock. As the path grows wider the mouth of the cave expands, revealing the full revelry of Deepwater Cavern. The roof of the cave stands some 100 feet above your head, thick stalactites stretch down from the darkness above. The roof is covered with a foggy substance that’s difficult to focus your eyes on.
The full cavern is enormous, spanning almost 1500 feet across at its widest points. The floor is split down the middle by the channel leading back out into the ocean, the other end of which opens up into a huge pool of ocean water in the center of the cave. This pool is about 300 feet across, and extends down farther than you can see, despite the crystal clear water. Merfolk, sirens, and elves can be seen swimming in and out of the channel and other underwater tunnels that lead down and out of sight.
Surrounding the huge ocean pool is a series of boardwalks and docks that wrap around the outside of the water, with a few bridges crossing over the center. The boardwalk is lined with buildings glowing with a warm yellow light, the sounds of dancing and singing mix with the smell of alcohol and cooking food.
As you approach the surprisingly large settlement, you can see all manner of people walking about: elegant Reigar, adorned with tattoos and piercings, their hair floating in the air as if it were underwater. You see Noctral elves strolling about and shouting cheers at the cantina, their skin a bone white color, in stark contrast to their appearance outside the cave. Some jump into the sea water, and swim into the many underwater passageways adorning the walls of the ocean channel. Several pirates stumble down the boardwalk, the alcohol on their breath noticeable from a good 10 feet away.
If players examine the foggy substance on the roof:
Have the players roll perception. 

If they get 20+, read this explanation:
A cloudy substance shifts ambiently across the roof of the cave almost 200 feet in the air. You can tell that it’s a cloud, because you can clearly see the silhouette blooming and falling in on itself the way clouds do, and because the substance wraps around the hanging stalactites as if it were a fog. But as you look at the fog itself, you have a hard time focusing on its form. Rather than having the bright and dark spots you would expect of a volumetric cloud like this, the surface of the substance has a strange parallax effect to it, that makes it incredibly difficult to focus on the actual form of the substance, almost as if the surface was incredibly far away, like a bright gray cloud far behind the actual cloud in the room. As you look, you are taken aback, as something begins to drift into view within the cloudy substance. You watch in shock as an enormous gold crown slowly floats across what you realize is the Astral Plane, and as it slowly drifts past, it reveals the old skull of a fallen god, long forgotten drifting amongst the ruins. You realize you are looking at a portal directly into the Astral Plane. They can point this event out to the rest of the party who can also observe the dead god drift across the view of the portal. 

If they get 15-19 read this explanation:
A cloudy substance shifts ambiently across the roof of the cave almost 200 feet in the air. You can tell that it’s a cloud, because you can clearly see the silhouette blooming and falling in on itself the way clouds do, and because the substance wraps around the hanging stalactites as if it were a fog. But as you look at the fog itself, you have a hard time focusing on its form. Rather than having the bright and dark spots you would expect of a volumetric cloud like this, the surface of the substance has a strange parallax effect to it, that makes it incredibly difficult to focus on the actual form of the substance.

If the character in question has been to or is familiar with the Astral Plane:
As you look at this strange, bright gray, void, a sense of familiarity, or recognition comes over you. You’re gazing into a vast, gray, nothingness. The vast, gray, nothingness. A nothingness that you recognize as the Astral Plane.

If the character is not familiar with the Astral Plane:
As you look at this strange, bright gray, void, you feel a vast nothingness, unlike you’ve ever experienced. It almost gives you the feeling of vertigo as you realize what you’re looking at continues on forever. This bright gray nothingness imprints itself in your memory in a way you will never forget. If the character ever sees or has the Astral Plane described to them after this, they will connect the two together and realize the cloudy substance is likely a portal to the Astral Plane.

If they get 5-15:
They fail to understand what they’re looking at, but can reasonably assume that the locals of this place would be easily able to answer should they ask.

If they get less than 5:
They have no idea what they’re looking at.


If players examine the pool of water in the middle:
